      "Identifies": " Magnesium level abnormalities that could impact muscle, nerve functioning, and bone health. ",
      "measures": "The quantity of magnesium present in a person’s blood. ",
      "price": 600,
      "testCategory": "Biochemistry"
    },
    "requisites": [
      {
        "value": "A blood sample is required; at times, fasting is necessary. "
      }
    ],
    "packages": [],
    "faqs": [
      {
        "question": "Is fasting necessary for a Magnesium Test?  ",
        "answer": "Not always, but specialists may require fasting for other associated electrolyte panels."
      },
      {
        "question": "Can medications affect magnesium levels?  ",
        "answer": "Indeed, diuretics, and antibiotics along with proton pump inhibitors will lower magnesium levels."
      },
      {
        "question": "What are signs of low magnesium?  ",
        "answer": "Symptoms include muscle cramps, tremors, seizures, abnormal heart rhythms, and fatigue."
      },
      {
        "question": "How can I correct low magnesium?  ",
        "answer": "Dietary adjustment or oral supplementation is usually sufficient but may require IV Magnesium Therapy depending on the condition’s severity."
      },
      {
        "question": "How often should magnesium levels be checked?  ",
        "answer": "With chronic kidney disease, diabetes, or on magnesium-altering medications, regular assessment is recommended."
      }
    ],
    "interpretations": {
      "title": "Interpreting the Results of Your Magnesium Test ",
      "cols": [
        "Condition/Findings",
        "Description",
        "Interpretation"
      ],
      "rows": [
        [
          "Normal Magnesium Level ",
          "Adults: 1.7 – 2.3 mg/dL ",
          "Balanced magnesium status; no immediate concerns. "
        ],
        [
          "Low Magnesium Level (Hypomagnesemia) ",
          "Magnesium below 1.7 mg/dL ",
          "Could indicate malnutrition, chronic diarrhea, alcoholism, or diabetes. "
        ],
        [
          "High Magnesium Level (Hypermagnesemia) ",
          "Magnesium above 2.3 mg/dL ",
          "Often associated with kidney failure, excessive magnesium supplementation, or dehydration. "
        ]
      ]
    },
